{"title_page": "Charles Macpherson Dobell", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell\n|image= Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt= \n|caption= [[John Singer Sargent]]: Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell, Oil on canvas, 1919.\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1869|06|22|df=yes}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1954|10|17|1869|06|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Quebec City]], Quebec\n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= 1890\u2013c.1920\n|rank= [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Eastern Force]]\n|battles= [[Second Boer War]]<br/>[[Boxer Rebellion]]<br/>[[First World War]]\n* [[Kamerun Campaign]]\n* [[First Battle of Gaza]]\n* [[Second Battle of Gaza]]\n|awards= [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]]<br/>[[Legion of Honour]] (France)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] '''Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|CMG|DSO}} (22 June 1869 \u2013 17 October 1954) was a Canadian soldier who served with the [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]] of the British Army.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Quebec City]], the son of [[Richard Reid Dobell]], an MP, and a grandson of [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] Sir [[David Lewis Macpherson]], Dobell was educated at the Rev. Canon Von Iffland's Private School, the Quebec High School and [[Charterhouse School]] in England. He graduated from the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] (college #221) in 1890. He was a lieutenant in the Hazara expedition of 1891 and took part with the International Forces in the occupation of the Island of [[Crete]], where he was promoted to major. He served during the [[Second Boer War]], where he was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]]. After serving in [[Nigeria]], he was promoted to lieutenant colonel. He served in China during the [[Boxer Rebellion]]. He was gazetted as Inspector-General of the West African Field Force, with the rank of brigadier general.\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], he fought in the [[Kamerun Campaign]] and was later promoted to lieutenant general. He served with the [[Egyptian Expeditionary Force]] in the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign]] under General Sir [[Archibald Murray]], but they were both replaced in 1917.\n\nIn the [[1915 New Year Honours]], he was made a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]. He was also made a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{no footnotes|date=April 2017}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/cyclopdiaofcan00charuoft|title=A cyclop\u00e6dia of Canadian biography|year=1919|work=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* [http://www.firstworldwar.com/bio/dobell.htm Biography of Charles Dobell at firstworldwar.com]\n\n===Books===\n*4237 Dr. Adrian Preston & Peter Dennis (Edited) \"Swords and Covenants\" Rowman And Littlefield, London. Croom Helm. 1976.\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Arthur Preston \"To Serve Canada: A History of the Royal Military College of Canada\" 1997 Toronto, [[University of Toronto Press]], 1969.\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Arthur Preston \"Canada's RMC \u2013 A History of Royal Military College\" Second Edition 1982\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Preston \"R.M.C. and Kingston: The effect of imperial and military influences on a Canadian community\" 1968 [[Kingston, Ontario]].\n*H1877 R. Guy C. Smith (editor) \"As You Were! Ex-Cadets Remember\". In 2 Volumes. Volume I: 1876\u20131918. Volume II: 1919\u20131984. [[Royal Military College of Canada|RMC]]. [[Kingston, Ontario]]. The R.M.C. Club of Canada. 1984\n-Winston S. Churchill \"Ian Hamilton's March\" Longmans,Green,and co, London (1 edition) 1900, page 405.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dobell, Charles}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:British Army generals of World War I]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Canadian Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Royal Military College of Canada alumni]]\n[[Category:Royal Welch Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Boxer Rebellion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell\n|image= Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell.jpg\n|image_size=\n|alt= \n|caption= [[John Singer Sargent]]: Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell, Oil on canvas, 1919\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1869|06|22|df=yes}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1954|10|17|1869|06|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[Quebec City]], Quebec\n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|branch= {{army|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears= 1890\u2013c.1920\n|rank= [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Eastern Force]]\n|battles= [[Second Boer War]]<br/>[[Boxer Rebellion]]<br/>[[First World War]]\n* [[Kamerun Campaign]]\n* [[First Battle of Gaza]]\n* [[Second Battle of Gaza]]\n|awards= [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]]<br/>[[Legion of Honour]] (France)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] '''Sir Charles Macpherson Dobell''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|CMG|DSO}} (22 June 1869 \u2013 17 October 1954) was a Canadian soldier who served with the [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]] of the British Army.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Quebec City]], the son of [[Richard Reid Dobell]], an MP, and a grandson of [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] Sir [[David Lewis Macpherson]], Dobell was educated at the Rev. Canon Von Iffland's Private School, the Quebec High School and [[Charterhouse School]] in England. He graduated from the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] (college #221) in 1890. He was a lieutenant in the Hazara expedition of 1891 and took part with the International Forces in the occupation of the Island of [[Crete]], where he was promoted to major. He served during the [[Second Boer War]], where he was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]]. After serving in [[Nigeria]], he was promoted to lieutenant colonel. He served in China during the [[Boxer Rebellion]]. He was gazetted as Inspector-General of the West African Field Force, with the rank of brigadier general.\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], he fought in the [[Kamerun Campaign]] and was later promoted to lieutenant general. He served with the [[Egyptian Expeditionary Force]] in the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign]] under General Sir [[Archibald Murray]], but they were both replaced in 1917.\n\nIn the [[1915 New Year Honours]], he was made a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]. He was also made a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{no footnotes|date=April 2017}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/cyclopdiaofcan00charuoft|title=A cyclop\u00e6dia of Canadian biography|year=1919|work=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* [http://www.firstworldwar.com/bio/dobell.htm Biography of Charles Dobell at firstworldwar.com]\n\n===Books===\n*4237 Dr. Adrian Preston & Peter Dennis (Edited) \"Swords and Covenants\" Rowman And Littlefield, London. Croom Helm. 1976.\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Arthur Preston \"To Serve Canada: A History of the Royal Military College of Canada\" 1997 Toronto, [[University of Toronto Press]], 1969.\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Arthur Preston \"Canada's RMC \u2013 A History of Royal Military College\" Second Edition 1982\n*H16511 Dr. Richard Preston \"R.M.C. and Kingston: The effect of imperial and military influences on a Canadian community\" 1968 [[Kingston, Ontario]].\n*H1877 R. Guy C. Smith (editor) \"As You Were! Ex-Cadets Remember\". In 2 Volumes. Volume I: 1876\u20131918. Volume II: 1919\u20131984. [[Royal Military College of Canada|RMC]]. [[Kingston, Ontario]]. The R.M.C. Club of Canada. 1984\n-Winston S. Churchill \"Ian Hamilton's March\" Longmans,Green,and co, London (1 edition) 1900, page 405.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dobell, Charles}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Second Boer War]]\n[[Category:British Army generals of World War I]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Canadian Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Royal Military College of Canada alumni]]\n[[Category:Royal Welch Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Boxer Rebellion]]\n", "name_user": "Amil2012", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Macpherson_Dobell"}
{"title_page": "Devoured (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Devoured \n| image          = File:Devoured 2012 movie poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| film name      = \n| director       = Greg Olliver\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Marc Landau\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = [[Marta Milans]]<br>Kara Jackson<br>Bruno Gunn\n| narrator       = \n| music          = Carly Paradis\n| cinematography = Lyle Vincent\n| editing        = Greg Olliver\n| studio         = Secret Weapon Films\n| distributor    = Gravitas Ventures \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|5|6|Bilbao Fantasy Film Festival}}\n| runtime        = 89 min\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English, Spanish\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!-- Please use condensed and rounded values. \u00a311.6 million vs. \u00a311,586,221 -->\n}}\n'''''Devoured''''' is a 2012 [[Drama Film|dramatic]] [[horror film]] that was directed by Greg Olliver and is his feature film [[directorial debut]].<ref name=aicn>{{cite web|title=AICN HORROR talks with director Greg Olliver about his atmospheric and haunting film DEVOURED! Plus a review!|url=https://aintitcool.com/node/68601|publisher=AICN|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> The film had its world premiere on May 6, 2012 at the Bilbao Fantasy Film Festival and stars [[Marta Milans]] as a hardworking young woman that begins to experience strange visions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Ryan|title=Greg Olliver's Devoured gets a release date|url=https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/greg-ollivers-devoured-gets-a-release-date-120|publisher=JoBlo|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nLourdes (Marta Milans) is a young woman from El Salvador that has come to New York City in hopes of raising enough money to help care for her ill son, who lives with Lourdes's mother back in her home country. She works in an upscale restaurant where her boss mistreats her, her boss's boyfriend sexually assaults her, and various men forcefully solicit her for sexual favors. Lourdes endures all of this as she cannot afford to lose her job and while she is reluctant to prostitute herself, she will do anything in order to raise enough money for her son's surgery. Her only solace is found in her phone calls to her son in El Salvador and her interactions with Frankie (Bruno Gunn), a firefighter that is the only person in New York who has shown Lourdes any true kindness. While cleaning the restaurant one night, Lourdes begins to experience strange visions where she sees strange shadowy figures that seem out to get her.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Marta Milans]] as Lourdes\n*Kara Jackson as Kristen\n*Bruno Gunn as Friendly Frankie Callahan\n*Tyler Hollinger as Billy\n*Luis Harris as Oliver\n*Sal Rendino as Henry\n*David Conley as Detective Cruthers\n*Jim O'Hare as Man in Black\n*Richard Alleman as Man Eating Alone\n*Eric Lommel as Kitchen Staff #1\n*Dixon Gutierrez as Kitchen Staff #2\n*Rennel Turner as Officer #1\n*Jaime Carrillo as Officer #2\n*Annie Lee Moffett as Lourdes' Old Friend\n*Amy Landon as Detective Sullivan\n\n==Reception==\nCritical reception for ''Devoured'' has been predominantly positive, and the film has received praise from multiple horror review websites.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gingold|first1=Michael|title=\"DEVOURED\" (Movie Review)|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/devoured-movie-review/|publisher=Fangoria|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ondechek|first1=David|title=Film Review: Devoured|url=https://horrornews.net/61092/devoured-2012/|publisher=HorrorNews.net|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> Opinions were polarized on the film's pacing, which some reviewers felt could deter some viewers while others saw it as adding to the movie's overall feel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Lauren|title=[Official Review] \u2018Devoured\u2019 Atmospheric With A Great Payoff!|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3145396/official-review-devoured-atmospheric-with-a-great-payoff/|publisher=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hallam|first1=Scott|title=Devoured (review)|url=https://dreadcentral.com/reviews/devoured-2014#axzz3CPpoXrDt|publisher=Dread Central|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Doro|first1=Paul|title=Review: Devoured is a Quiet Thriller That Creeps Up On You|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/364121-review-devoured-quiet-thriller-creeps/|publisher=STYD|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> ''We Got This Covered'' gave ''Devoured'' four out of five stars and wrote \"From magnificent production to all around tantalizing psychological horror, Devoured will surely give you a good haunting, as well as present enough substance to take a hearty bite out of along the way.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Donato|first1=Matt|title=Devoured [NYCHFF 2012] Review|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/devoured-review/#!bP24GA|publisher=WGTC|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n*''Best Director Award'' at the [[New York City Horror Film Festival]] (2012, won)<ref name=NYCHF>{{cite web|title=2012 Awards|url=http://nychorrorfest.com/past-festivals/1/|publisher=NYCHF|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n*''Best Actress Award'' at the [[New York City Horror Film Festival]] (2012, won - Marta Milans)<ref name=NYCHF />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2010976}}\n\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2012 horror films]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2012 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Devoured \n| image          = File:Devoured 2012 movie poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical poster\n| film name      = \n| director       = Greg Olliver\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Marc Landau\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| starring       = Marta Milans<br>Kara Jackson<br>Bruno Gunn\n| narrator       = \n| music          = Carly Paradis\n| cinematography = Lyle Vincent\n| editing        = Greg Olliver\n| studio         = Secret Weapon Films\n| distributor    = Gravitas Ventures \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|5|6|Bilbao Fantasy Film Festival}}\n| runtime        = 89 min\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English, Spanish\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!-- Please use condensed and rounded values. \u00a311.6 million vs. \u00a311,586,221 -->\n}}\n'''''Devoured''''' is a 2012 [[Drama Film|dramatic]] [[horror film]] that was directed by Greg Olliver and is his feature film [[directorial debut]].<ref name=aicn>{{cite web|title=AICN HORROR talks with director Greg Olliver about his atmospheric and haunting film DEVOURED! Plus a review!|url=https://aintitcool.com/node/68601|publisher=AICN|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> The film had its world premiere on May 6, 2012 at the Bilbao Fantasy Film Festival and stars Marta Milans as a hardworking young woman that begins to experience strange visions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Ryan|title=Greg Olliver's Devoured gets a release date|url=https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/greg-ollivers-devoured-gets-a-release-date-120|publisher=JoBlo|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nLourdes (Marta Milans) is a young woman from El Salvador that has come to New York City in hopes of raising enough money to help care for her ill son, who lives with Lourdes's mother back in her home country. She works in an upscale restaurant where her boss mistreats her, her boss's boyfriend sexually assaults her, and various men forcefully solicit her for sexual favors. Lourdes endures all of this as she cannot afford to lose her job and while she is reluctant to prostitute herself, she will do anything in order to raise enough money for her son's surgery. Her only solace is found in her phone calls to her son in El Salvador and her interactions with Frankie (Bruno Gunn), a firefighter that is the only person in New York who has shown Lourdes any true kindness. While cleaning the restaurant one night, Lourdes begins to experience strange visions where she sees strange shadowy figures that seem out to get her.\n\n==Cast==\n*Marta Milans as Lourdes\n*Kara Jackson as Kristen\n*Bruno Gunn as Friendly Frankie Callahan\n*Tyler Hollinger as Billy\n*Luis Harris as Oliver\n*Sal Rendino as Henry\n*David Conley as Detective Cruthers\n*Jim O'Hare as Man in Black\n*Richard Alleman as Man Eating Alone\n*Eric Lommel as Kitchen Staff #1\n*Dixon Gutierrez as Kitchen Staff #2\n*Rennel Turner as Officer #1\n*Jaime Carrillo as Officer #2\n*Annie Lee Moffett as Lourdes' Old Friend\n*Amy Landon as Detective Sullivan\n\n==Reception==\nCritical reception for ''Devoured'' has been predominantly positive, and the film has received praise from multiple horror review websites.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gingold|first1=Michael|title=\"DEVOURED\" (Movie Review)|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/devoured-movie-review/|publisher=Fangoria|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ondechek|first1=David|title=Film Review: Devoured|url=https://horrornews.net/61092/devoured-2012/|publisher=HorrorNews.net|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> Opinions were polarized on the film's pacing, which some reviewers felt could deter some viewers while others saw it as adding to the movie's overall feel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Lauren|title=[Official Review] \u2018Devoured\u2019 Atmospheric With A Great Payoff!|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3145396/official-review-devoured-atmospheric-with-a-great-payoff/|publisher=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hallam|first1=Scott|title=Devoured (review)|url=https://dreadcentral.com/reviews/devoured-2014#axzz3CPpoXrDt|publisher=Dread Central|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Doro|first1=Paul|title=Review: Devoured is a Quiet Thriller That Creeps Up On You|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/364121-review-devoured-quiet-thriller-creeps/|publisher=STYD|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref> ''We Got This Covered'' gave ''Devoured'' four out of five stars and wrote \"From magnificent production to all around tantalizing psychological horror, Devoured will surely give you a good haunting, as well as present enough substance to take a hearty bite out of along the way.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Donato|first1=Matt|title=Devoured [NYCHFF 2012] Review|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/devoured-review/#!bP24GA|publisher=WGTC|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n*''Best Director Award'' at the [[New York City Horror Film Festival]] (2012, won)<ref name=NYCHF>{{cite web|title=2012 Awards|url=http://nychorrorfest.com/past-festivals/1/|publisher=NYCHF|accessdate=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n*''Best Actress Award'' at the [[New York City Horror Film Festival]] (2012, won - Marta Milans)<ref name=NYCHF />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2010976}}\n\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2012 horror films]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2012 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Alrofficial", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devoured_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Dallen Stanford", "text_new": "[[File:World Rugby commentator Dallen Stanford.jpg|thumb|World Rugby commentator Dallen Stanford interviews the King of Sevens, Waisale Serevi.]]\n\n'''Dallen Stanford''' (born May 16, 1979) is a South African born, former American [[rugby union]] sevens player,<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford's varsity reunion in George |url=http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0,25883,3829_2950142,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114731/http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0,25883,3829_2950142,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 September 2015 |website=Planet Rugby |publisher=Planet Rugby |accessdate=7 December 2007 |ref=1 }}</ref> and current rugby commentator based in the United States. \n\nStanford was selected for the [[United States national rugby sevens team|USA Rugby Sevens]] team by head coach [[Al Caravelli]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=USA player pool for World Sevens Series|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/scrum/rugby/story/66086.html|website=ESPN Scrum|publisher=ESPN Scrum|accessdate=14 October 2006|ref=2}}</ref> The halfback played in 12 [[World Rugby Sevens Series|Sevens World Series]] events from 2007-2009 and was a traveling reserve for the 2009 [[Rugby World Cup Sevens|Sevens Rugby World Cup]] in [[Dubai]].\n\nIn November 2014, Stanford received the Athletes in Excellence Award from [[The Foundation for Global Sports Development]], in recognition of his community service efforts and work with youth through Play Rugby USA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teamusa.org/News/2014/November/21/Eight-Olympians-Paralympians-Named-Athletes-in-Excellence|title=Eight Olympians, Paralympians Named Athletes In Excellence|newspaper=Team USA|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref>\n\nStanford is the Director of Sports Partnerships for [http://www.fobcus.org/ Friends of the British Council] working with [[Premiership Rugby]] on their corporate social responsibility program in the USA. One of the initiatives is a partnership with [[USA Rugby]] for an [https://www.premiershiprugbyscholarships.co.uk/ international rugby coaching experience to Premiership Rugby] in England. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiershiprugbyscholarships.co.uk/|title=Premiership Rugby Scholarship|website=Premiership Rugby Scholarships|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n== Playing and Coaching Career ==\nStanford attended [[Rondebosch Boys' High School]] and played alongside Springboks [[Gcobani Bobo]] and [[Hanyani Shimange]] during 1996/1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rondebosch Boys' High School|url=http://schoolsevens.villagerfc.co.za/participating-teams/rondebosch-high-school/|website=Villager Sevens|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref> He studied [[Marketing]] at the [[Cape Technikon]], and played rugby at the [[University of Cape Town]] (UCT), captaining the u21A [http://ikeytigers.com/ Ikey Tigers] side to a rare unbeaten season in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ikeytigers.com/catching-up-with-ikey-legend-dallen-stanford/|title=Catching up with Ikey Legend Dallen Stanford|website=UCT RFC|publisher=UCT RFC|accessdate=2019-04-23}}</ref> He represented UCT 1st XV from 1999-2002 at outside center, and was part of the famous 8-8 draw with the University of Stellenbosch (Maties) during the 2002 InterVarsity at [[Danie Craven Stadium]], and UCT's 34-24 win over [[Stellenbosch]] in the return fixture at the Green Mile.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rugby: UCT conquers the mighty Maties|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/mondaypaper/archives/?id=3283|website=University of Cape Town|accessdate=16 September 2002}}</ref> \nAfter moving to the United States, Stanford represented the Occidental Olde Boys (2003-2006), Belmont Shore Rugby Football Club (2007-2010), [[Austin Huns]] Rugby Football Club (2010-2011) and toured with the Pacific Coast Grizzlies (Hong Kong 10s, Singapore 7s), Atlantis Rugby (Rome 7s, Benidorm 7s) and [https://www.tigerrugby.com/ Tiger Rugby] (Nelson Mandela Bay 7s, Cancun 7s, RugbyTown 7s).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/|title=The Rugby Corner: About Dallen Stanford|website=The Rugby Corner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\nAt [[Belmont Shore RFC|Belmont Shore Rugby Football Club]] Stanford was a part of the [[Rugby Super League (United States)|Super League]] Championship team in 2007 and the [[USA Rugby]] Club 7s National Championship side in 2009 and runners-up in 2008 and 2010. Stanford was the tournament's top point scorer at the USA Rugby Club 7s [[National Championship]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/|title=The Rugby Corner: About Dallen Stanford|website=The Rugby Corner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter retiring from international rugby, Stanford represented [[Team USA]] at the 2013 [[Maccabiah Games|World Maccabiah Games]] in Israel, captaining the [[USA Rugby]] squad to Gold in 7s and Bronze in XVs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maccabiusa.com/maccabi-blog-rugby-with-dallen-stanford/|title=Maccabi Blog- Rugby with Dallen Stanford|last=admin|date=2014-12-05|website=Maccabi USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was named MVP of the inaugural 7s tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maccabiusa.com/rugby_coaches/|title=MACCABI USA RUGBY ANNOUNCES COACHING STAFF FOR 2015 PAN AMERICAN MACCABI GAMES|last=admin|date=2015-01-30|website=Maccabi USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> In 2015, Stanford represented Team USA as a player/coach at the 13th [[Maccabiah Games|Pan American Maccabi Games]], held in Santiago, Chile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usarugby.org/2015/10/maccabi-usa-rugby-team-announced-for-2015-pan-american-maccabi-games/|title=Maccabi USA rugby team announced for 2015 Pan American Maccabi Games|website=USA Rugby|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was one of three USA flag bearers for the Opening Ceremonies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.maccabiusa.com/site/MessageViewer?dlv_id=14432&em_id=2847.0|title=Maccabi USA|website=support.maccabiusa.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Team USA won Gold in 7s and Silver in XVs, with Stanford captaining the sevens squad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goffrugbyreport.com/tags/maccabi-rugby|title=Maccabi Rugby|website=Goff Rugby Report|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2011 to 2017, Stanford was the [[Los Angeles]] Program Director for non-profit [https://playrugbyusa.org/ Play Rugby USA] - whose mission is developing youth through rugby, using flag rugby as a vehicle for social change.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playrugbyusa.com/los-angeles/|title=Play Rugby USA Los Angeles|website=PlayRugbyUSA|publisher=Play Rugby USA|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> He was the Media manager for USA Rugby at the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in New Zealand and [[Rugby World Cup Sevens|2013 Sevens Rugby World Cup]] in Russia.\n\nStanford has coached the [[Austin Huns|Austin Huns RFC]], Austin Valkyries, [[University of Texas at Austin]] and was Head Coach of the [[Occidental College]] Men's RFC from 2011 to 2013. Occidental College claimed their first National title in rugby by winning the NSCRO 7s at the 2013 [[Collegiate Rugby Championship]] in Philadelphia.\n\n==Broadcasting Career==\nIn 2016 Stanford made his broadcasting debut on the [[World Rugby Sevens Series|HSBC Sevens World Series]] announcing the Men's [[USA Sevens|USA 7s]] (Las Vegas) and [[Canada Sevens|Canada 7s]] (Vancouver) as well as the Women's Atlanta 7s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world.rugby/sevens-series/news/141911?lang=en|title=World Series heads to North America|last=worldrugby.org|website=www.world.rugby|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Stanford has regularly featured on the HSBC Sevens World Series commentating the [[USA Sevens|USA 7s]] (Las Vegas 2016, 2017, 2018 & 2019, Los Angeles 2020), [[Canada Sevens|Canada 7s]] (Vancouver 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020), [[Singapore Sevens|Singapore 7s]] (2018, 2019), Dubai 7s (2019), Cape Town 7s (2019) and the 2018 [[Rugby World Cup Sevens]] in San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/fly-like-eagle-world-cup-brings-usa-sevens-full-circle/|title=Fly like an Eagle: World Cup brings USA Sevens full circle|website=www.rugbypass.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was one of the leading play-by-play commentators for [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States - appearing on [[CBS Sports Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glendaleraptors.com/news/dallen-stanford-and-brian-vizard-set-to-call-major-league-rugby-action-on-cbs-sports-network|title=Dallen Stanford and Brian Vizard Set to Call Major League Rugby Action on CBS Sports Network|website=Glendale Raptors|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> in 2018, 2019 and 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/major-league-rugby-qa-mlr-commentator-dallen-stanford/|title=Major League Rugby: Q&A with MLR commentator Dallen Stanford|website=www.rugbypass.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Stanford was one of the lead voices for the 2019 World Rugby U20s Championship in Rosario, Argentina, featuring in several video reviews and previews called [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NggIt8wzRm4&t=1s Commentators Cut]<ref>{{Citation|last=World Rugby|title=Stanford and Tenana discuss World Rugby U20s Top Performers|date=2019-06-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MAkkx5a3jt0|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>.\n\nStanford made history as the first South African and first American to announce a [[Rugby World Cup]] for World Rugby on the World Feed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.rugby/2019/08/from-playing-to-broadcasting/|title=Eagle Alumni Spotlight: Dallen Stanford, From Playing to Broadcasting|date=2019-08-23|website=USA Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> He was one of four lead commentators selected by World Rugby to announce the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] in Japan. Stanford worked with analyst [[Joel Stransky]] and sideline commentator [[Santiago G\u00f3mez Cora|Santiago Gomez-Cora]] covering 10 pool matches, including: Italy v Namibia, Wales v Georgia, England v USA, Argentina v Tonga, Scotland v Samoa, Ireland v Russia, Japan v Samoa, South Africa v Canada, Ireland v Samoa and Wales v Uruguay. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.rugby/2019/08/from-playing-to-broadcasting/|title=Eagle Alumni Spotlight: Dallen Stanford, From Playing to Broadcasting|date=2019-08-23|website=USA Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Stanford's most popular #RWC2019 one-liners included \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LYcEPi9Edqo Kotaro Matsushima - he's so dangerous - Freddy Krueger has nightmares about him!]\" (Japan v Samoa) and \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7cv5F7fbzM Cobus Reinach - he's more dangerous than climate change!]\" (South Africa v Canada).\n\nStanford has been the show host for the [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCMoZPFih4Y7anW2MOPG2aPQ Colorado Raptors] weekly highlights in 2018, 2019 and 2020. 'Pardon My Take' co-host PFT Commentator said in an interview in March, 2020: \u201cI would say that it\u2019s 50 percent the success of the sevens team and 50 percent having Dallen Stanford on all of those calls that make it on social media because he\u2019s an electric dude.\"<ref>https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/its-time-to-take-notice-ft-a-conversation-with-pardon-my-takes-pft-commenter/</ref>. Since 2012 Stanford has commentated 44 Internationals.<ref>https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanford, Dallen}}\n[[Category:American people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Rondebosch Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African rugby sevens players]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:World Rugby commentator Dallen Stanford.jpg|thumb|World Rugby commentator Dallen Stanford interviews the King of Sevens, Waisale Serevi.]]\n\n'''Dallen Stanford''' (born May 16, 1979) is a South African born, former American [[rugby union]] sevens player,<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford's varsity reunion in George |url=http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0,25883,3829_2950142,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114731/http://www.planetrugby.com/story/0,25883,3829_2950142,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 September 2015 |website=Planet Rugby |publisher=Planet Rugby |accessdate=7 December 2007 |ref=1 }}</ref> and current rugby commentator based in the United States. \n\nStanford was selected for the [[United States national rugby sevens team|USA Rugby Sevens]] team by head coach [[Al Caravelli]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=USA player pool for World Sevens Series|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/scrum/rugby/story/66086.html|website=ESPN Scrum|publisher=ESPN Scrum|accessdate=14 October 2006|ref=2}}</ref> The halfback played in 12 [[World Rugby Sevens Series|Sevens World Series]] events from 2007-2009 and was a traveling reserve for the 2009 [[Rugby World Cup Sevens|Sevens Rugby World Cup]] in [[Dubai]].\n\nIn November 2014, Stanford received the Athletes in Excellence Award from [[The Foundation for Global Sports Development]], in recognition of his community service efforts and work with youth through Play Rugby USA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.teamusa.org/News/2014/November/21/Eight-Olympians-Paralympians-Named-Athletes-in-Excellence|title=Eight Olympians, Paralympians Named Athletes In Excellence|newspaper=Team USA|access-date=2017-02-08}}</ref>\n\nStanford is the Director of Sports Partnerships for [http://www.fobcus.org/ Friends of the British Council] working with [[Premiership Rugby]] on their corporate social responsibility program in the USA. One of the initiatives is a partnership with [[USA Rugby]] for an [https://www.premiershiprugbyscholarships.co.uk/ international rugby coaching experience to Premiership Rugby] in England. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiershiprugbyscholarships.co.uk/|title=Premiership Rugby Scholarship|website=Premiership Rugby Scholarships|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\n== Playing and Coaching Career ==\nStanford attended [[Rondebosch Boys' High School]] and played alongside Springboks [[Gcobani Bobo]] and [[Hanyani Shimange]] during 1996/1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rondebosch Boys' High School|url=http://schoolsevens.villagerfc.co.za/participating-teams/rondebosch-high-school/|website=Villager Sevens|accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref> He studied [[Marketing]] at the [[Cape Technikon]], and played rugby at the [[University of Cape Town]] (UCT), captaining the u21A [http://ikeytigers.com/ Ikey Tigers] side to a rare unbeaten season in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ikeytigers.com/catching-up-with-ikey-legend-dallen-stanford/|title=Catching up with Ikey Legend Dallen Stanford|website=UCT RFC|publisher=UCT RFC|accessdate=2019-04-23}}</ref> He represented UCT 1st XV from 1999-2002 at outside center, and was part of the famous 8-8 draw with the University of Stellenbosch (Maties) during the 2002 InterVarsity at [[Danie Craven Stadium]], and UCT's 34-24 win over [[Stellenbosch]] in the return fixture at the Green Mile.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rugby: UCT conquers the mighty Maties|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/mondaypaper/archives/?id=3283|website=University of Cape Town|accessdate=16 September 2002}}</ref> \nAfter moving to the United States, Stanford represented the Occidental Olde Boys (2003-2006), Belmont Shore Rugby Football Club (2007-2010), [[Austin Huns]] Rugby Football Club (2010-2011) and toured with the Pacific Coast Grizzlies (Hong Kong 10s, Singapore 7s), Atlantis Rugby (Rome 7s, Benidorm 7s) and [https://www.tigerrugby.com/ Tiger Rugby] (Nelson Mandela Bay 7s, Cancun 7s, RugbyTown 7s).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/|title=The Rugby Corner: About Dallen Stanford|website=The Rugby Corner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\nAt [[Belmont Shore RFC|Belmont Shore Rugby Football Club]] Stanford was a part of the [[Rugby Super League (United States)|Super League]] Championship team in 2007 and the [[USA Rugby]] Club 7s National Championship side in 2009 and runners-up in 2008 and 2010. Stanford was the tournament's top point scorer at the USA Rugby Club 7s [[National Championship]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/|title=The Rugby Corner: About Dallen Stanford|website=The Rugby Corner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter retiring from international rugby, Stanford represented [[Team USA]] at the 2013 [[Maccabiah Games|World Maccabiah Games]] in Israel, captaining the [[USA Rugby]] squad to Gold in 7s and Bronze in XVs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maccabiusa.com/maccabi-blog-rugby-with-dallen-stanford/|title=Maccabi Blog- Rugby with Dallen Stanford|last=admin|date=2014-12-05|website=Maccabi USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was named MVP of the inaugural 7s tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maccabiusa.com/rugby_coaches/|title=MACCABI USA RUGBY ANNOUNCES COACHING STAFF FOR 2015 PAN AMERICAN MACCABI GAMES|last=admin|date=2015-01-30|website=Maccabi USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> In 2015, Stanford represented Team USA as a player/coach at the 13th [[Maccabiah Games|Pan American Maccabi Games]], held in Santiago, Chile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usarugby.org/2015/10/maccabi-usa-rugby-team-announced-for-2015-pan-american-maccabi-games/|title=Maccabi USA rugby team announced for 2015 Pan American Maccabi Games|website=USA Rugby|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was one of three USA flag bearers for the Opening Ceremonies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://support.maccabiusa.com/site/MessageViewer?dlv_id=14432&em_id=2847.0|title=Maccabi USA|website=support.maccabiusa.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Team USA won Gold in 7s and Silver in XVs, with Stanford captaining the sevens squad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goffrugbyreport.com/tags/maccabi-rugby|title=Maccabi Rugby|website=Goff Rugby Report|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2011 to 2017, Stanford was the [[Los Angeles]] Program Director for non-profit [https://playrugbyusa.org/ Play Rugby USA] - whose mission is developing youth through rugby, using flag rugby as a vehicle for social change.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playrugbyusa.com/los-angeles/|title=Play Rugby USA Los Angeles|website=PlayRugbyUSA|publisher=Play Rugby USA|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> He was the Media manager for USA Rugby at the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in New Zealand and [[Rugby World Cup Sevens|2013 Sevens Rugby World Cup]] in Russia.\n\nStanford has coached the [[Austin Huns|Austin Huns RFC]], Austin Valkyries, [[University of Texas at Austin]] and was Head Coach of the [[Occidental College]] Men's RFC from 2011 to 2013. Occidental College claimed their first National title in rugby by winning the NSCRO 7s at the 2013 [[Collegiate Rugby Championship]] in Philadelphia.\n\n==Broadcasting Career==\nIn 2016 Stanford made his broadcasting debut on the [[World Rugby Sevens Series|HSBC Sevens World Series]] announcing the Men's [[USA Sevens|USA 7s]] (Las Vegas) and [[Canada Sevens|Canada 7s]] (Vancouver) as well as the Women's Atlanta 7s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world.rugby/sevens-series/news/141911?lang=en|title=World Series heads to North America|last=worldrugby.org|website=www.world.rugby|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Stanford has regularly featured on the HSBC Sevens World Series commentating the [[USA Sevens|USA 7s]] (Las Vegas 2016, 2017, 2018 & 2019, Los Angeles 2020), [[Canada Sevens|Canada 7s]] (Vancouver 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020), [[Singapore Sevens|Singapore 7s]] (2018, 2019), Dubai 7s (2019), Cape Town 7s (2019) and the 2018 [[Rugby World Cup Sevens]] in San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/fly-like-eagle-world-cup-brings-usa-sevens-full-circle/|title=Fly like an Eagle: World Cup brings USA Sevens full circle|website=www.rugbypass.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> He was one of the leading play-by-play commentators for [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States - appearing on [[CBS Sports Network]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glendaleraptors.com/news/dallen-stanford-and-brian-vizard-set-to-call-major-league-rugby-action-on-cbs-sports-network|title=Dallen Stanford and Brian Vizard Set to Call Major League Rugby Action on CBS Sports Network|website=Glendale Raptors|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> in 2018, 2019 and 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/major-league-rugby-qa-mlr-commentator-dallen-stanford/|title=Major League Rugby: Q&A with MLR commentator Dallen Stanford|website=www.rugbypass.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Stanford was one of the lead voices for the 2019 World Rugby U20s Championship in Rosario, Argentina, featuring in several video reviews and previews called [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NggIt8wzRm4&t=1s Commentators Cut]<ref>{{Citation|last=World Rugby|title=Stanford and Tenana discuss World Rugby U20s Top Performers|date=2019-06-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MAkkx5a3jt0|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>.\n\nStanford made history as the first South African and first American to announce a [[Rugby World Cup]] for World Rugby on the World Feed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.rugby/2019/08/from-playing-to-broadcasting/|title=Eagle Alumni Spotlight: Dallen Stanford, From Playing to Broadcasting|date=2019-08-23|website=USA Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> He was one of four lead commentators selected by World Rugby to announce the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] in Japan. Stanford worked with analyst [[Joel Stransky]] and sideline commentator [[Santiago G\u00f3mez Cora|Santiago Gomez-Cora]] covering 10 pool matches, including: Italy v Namibia, Wales v Georgia, England v USA, Argentina v Tonga, Scotland v Samoa, Ireland v Russia, Japan v Samoa, South Africa v Canada, Ireland v Samoa and Wales v Uruguay. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usa.rugby/2019/08/from-playing-to-broadcasting/|title=Eagle Alumni Spotlight: Dallen Stanford, From Playing to Broadcasting|date=2019-08-23|website=USA Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> Stanford's most popular #RWC2019 one-liners included \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LYcEPi9Edqo Kotaro Matsushima - he's so dangerous - Freddy Krueger has nightmares about him!]\" (Japan v Samoa) and \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G7cv5F7fbzM Cobus Reinach - he's more dangerous than climate change!]\" (South Africa v Canada).\n\nStanford has been the show host for the [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCMoZPFih4Y7anW2MOPG2aPQ Colorado Raptors] weekly highlights in 2018, 2019 and 2020. 'Pardon My Take' co-host PFT Commentator said in an interview in March, 2020: \u201cI would say that it\u2019s 50 percent the success of the sevens team and 50 percent having Dallen Stanford on all of those calls that make it on social media because he\u2019s an electric dude.\" [https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/its-time-to-take-notice-ft-a-conversation-with-pardon-my-takes-pft-commenter/]. Since 2012 Stanford has commentated 44 Internationals.<ref>https://www.therugbycorner.com/about/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanford, Dallen}}\n[[Category:American people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:United States international rugby sevens players]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Rondebosch Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African rugby sevens players]]\n", "name_user": "USAR1001", "label": "safe", "comment": "References", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallen_Stanford"}
{"title_page": "Greek Orthodox Church during the Yugoslav wars", "text_new": "{{db-attack|blanked=yes|help=off}}\n\nThe '''Greek Orthodox Church during the Yugoslav Wars''' played a major role in the geopolitical relations between the states of [[Serbia]] and [[Greece]]. The Greek Orthodox Church supported materially and morally the Bosnian Serb leadership in the [[Bosnian War]]. Its stance was linked to Greek foreign policy of the early 1990s that dictated the creation of an \"Orthodox arc\" between Orthodox states in the Balkans.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruegg |first1=Francois |last2=Boscoboinik |first2=Andrea |title=De Palerme \u00c0 Penang |date=2010 |publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster |isbn=3643800622 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9e7mUom7YcC&pg=PA154}}</ref> The Greek Orthodox Church traditionally pushed for closer geopolitical relations with Christian Orthodox countries. The election of [[Christodoulos of Athens]] as Archbishop of Greece in 1998 signified the turn of the leadership of the Greek Orthodox Church to an openly anti-NATO and anti-western stance in the [[Kosovo War]] with the use of its influence as a pressure tool to influence Greek state policy towards a pro-Serbian/Yugoslav stance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kavakas |first1=Dimitrios |title=Greece and Spain in European Foreign Policy: The Influence of Southern Member States in Common Foreign and Security Policy |date=2017 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1351808559 |page=129 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BL42DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT129}}</ref>\n\nThe politicization of the Greek Orthodox Church in the period of the Yugoslav Wars has been dubbed as one of the most important political developments in Greece in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Michas |first1=Takis |title=Unholy Alliance: Greece and Milo\u0161evi\u0107's Serbia |date=2002 |publisher=Texas A&M University Press |isbn=158544183X |page=109 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_kcAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{db-attack|blanked=yes|help=off}}\n\nThe '''Greek Orthodox Church during the Yugoslav Wars''' played a major role in the geopolitical relations between the states of [[Serbia]] and [[Greece]]. The Greek Orthodox Church supported materially and morally the Bosnian Serb leadership in the [[Bosnian War]]. Its stance was linked to Greek foreign policy of the early 1990s that dictated the creation of an \"Orthodox arc\" between Orthodox states in the Balkans.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ruegg |first1=Francois |last2=Boscoboinik |first2=Andrea |title=De Palerme \u00c0 Penang |date=2010 |publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster |isbn=3643800622 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9e7mUom7YcC&pg=PA154}}</ref> The Greek Orthodox Church traditionally pushed for closer geopolitical relations with Christian Orthodox countries. The election of [[Christodoulos of Athens]] as Archbishop of Greece in 1998 signified the turn of the leadership of the Greek Orthodox Church to an openly anti-NATO and anti-western stance in the [[Kosovo War]] with the use of its influence as a pressure tool to influence policy to influence a Greek state policy towards a pro-Serbian/Yugoslav stance.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kavakas |first1=Dimitrios |title=Greece and Spain in European Foreign Policy: The Influence of Southern Member States in Common Foreign and Security Policy |date=2017 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=1351808559 |page=129 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BL42DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT129}}</ref>\n\nThe politicization of the Greek Orthodox Church in the period of the Yugoslav Wars has been dubbed as one of the most important political developments in Greece in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Michas |first1=Takis |title=Unholy Alliance: Greece and Milo\u0161evi\u0107's Serbia |date=2002 |publisher=Texas A&M University Press |isbn=158544183X |page=109 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_kcAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Maleschreiber", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_Orthodox_Church_during_the_Yugoslav_wars"}
{"title_page": "Alfred T. Andreas", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  =\n|name              =Alfred Theodore Andreas\n|honorific_suffix  =\n|image         =\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =May 29, 1839\n|birth_date    ={{birth date|1839|05|29}}\n|death_date    ={{Death date and age|1900|02|10|1839|05|29}}\n|birth_place   =Amity, Orange County, New York\n|death_place   =New Rochelle, New York\n|placeofburial =Oakdale Memorial Gardens, Davenport, Iowa\n|placeofburial_label =\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      =\n|birth_name    =Alfred Theodore Andreas\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States|1865|23px}}\n|branch        =[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|serviceyears  =1861\u20131865\n|rank          =[[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n|unit          =[[12th Illinois Infantry]], Company G\n|commands      =\n|battles       =[[American Civil War]]\n*[[Battle of Shiloh]]\n*[[Siege of Corinth]]\n*[[Second Battle of Corinth]]\n*[[Battle of Resaca]]\n*[[Battle of Atlanta]]\n*[[Battle of Jonesborough]]\n*[[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]]\n*[[Battle of Bentonville]]\n|battles_label =\n|awards        =\n|memorials     =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Sophia Lyter|1865|1900|reason=death}}\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =Book publisher\n|signature     =\n}}\n'''Alfred Theodore Andreas''' (May 29, 1839 &ndash; February 10, 1900) was an American book publisher and historian.\n\n== Life ==\nHe was born in [[Amity, Orange County, New York|Amity]], [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]], New York, on May 29, 1839.\n\nAfter acquiring an education, he moved to [[Dubuque, Iowa]], where he taught school for some years and conducted business. In 1860, he moved to Illinois.  He enlisted in Company G, [[12th Illinois Infantry]] and served through the American Civil War, rising through the ranks to become a division [[commissary]], serving with Sherman on the [[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]] and the Carolina campaigns.<ref name=\"HudsonBergman2009\">{{cite book|author1=David Hudson|author2=Marvin Bergman|author3=Loren Horton|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Iowa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v-cdBfPrxfUC&pg=PA18|date=1 May 2009|publisher=University of Iowa Press|isbn=978-1-58729-724-3|pages=18\u201319|chapter=Alfred Theodore Andreas|others=Mary R. Mcinroy}}</ref> After peace was restored, he moved to [[Davenport, Iowa]], married and for several years was engaged in compiling and publishing county and State atlases, in partnership with [[John Milton Lyter]], who became mayor in 1870. In 1875, he completed and published his greatest work, which was an \"Illustrated Historical Atlas of Iowa.\" It was accurate and became an official authority for real estate dealers, county and State officers. Although many made him substantial profit, others, including his Minnesota and Indiana atlases, were financial failures.<ref name=\"HudsonBergman2009\"/>  Later Andreas moved to Chicago and organized the \u201cWestern Historical Company,\u201d and took up historical writing, publishing a three-volume ''History of Chicago''. He died at [[New Rochelle, New York]], on February 10, 1900.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gue|first=Benjamin F.|title=History of Iowa From the Earliest Times to the Beginning of the Twentieth Century/Volume 4|date=1903|publisher=Century Historical Company|location=New York City|page=7|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/History_of_Iowa_From_the_Earliest_Times_to_the_Beginning_of_the_Twentieth_Century/4/Alfred_T._Andreas}}</ref>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n*An illustrated historical atlas of Hancock County, Illinois (1874)<ref>[https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto00andr An illustrated historical atlas of Hancock County, Illinois]</ref>\n*An Illustrated Historical Atlas of the State of Minnesota (1874)<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Ristow | first1 = Walter W. | year = 1966 | title = Alfred T. Andreas and His Minnesota Atlas | journal = [[Minnesota History (journal)|Minnesota History]] | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 120\u2013129 | publisher =  Minnesota Historical Society Press | jstor = 20177838  | url =  | format = }}</ref>\n*Illustrated Historical Atlas of Iowa (1875)\n*Illustrated historical atlas of the State of Indiana  (1876)<ref>[http://indiamond6.ulib.iupui.edu/cdm/ref/collection/HistAtlas/id/4257 Illustrated historical atlas of the State of Indiana] at Historic Indiana Atlases</ref>\n*History of the State of Nebraska (1882)<ref>[http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ne/topic/resources/andreas/ History of the State of Nebraska]</ref>\n*History of the State of Kansas (1883)<ref>[http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/digital/collections/cul/texts/ldpd_8627113_002/index.html History of the State of Kansas] at [[Columbia University Libraries]]</ref>\n*History of Cook County Illinois (1884)\n*Historical Atlas of Dakota (1884)\n*History of Chicago (3 vols., 1884\u201386)<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historychicagoo00andrgoog History of Chicago (1975 ed.)]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[:File:Christ Church Red Wing 1874.jpg|Christ Episcopal Church (Red Wing, MN), engraving from the Minnesota Atlas]]\n*{{Find a Grave|30685421|Capt Alfred Theodore Andreas}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreas, Alfred T.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Warwick, New York]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People of Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Davenport, Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|honorific_prefix  =\n|name              =Alfred Theodore Andreas\n|honorific_suffix  =\n|image         =\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =May 29, 1839\n|birth_date    ={{birth date|1839|05|29}}\n|death_date    ={{Death date and age|1900|02|10|1839|05|29}}\n|birth_place   =Amity, Orange County, New York\n|death_place   =New Rochelle, New York\n|placeofburial =Oakdale Memorial Gardens, Davenport, Iowa\n|placeofburial_label =\n|placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nickname      =\n|birth_name    =Alfred Theodore Andreas\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States|1865|23px}}\n|branch        =[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|serviceyears  =1861\u20131865\n|rank          =[[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|servicenumber = <!--Do not use data from primary sources such as service records.-->\n|unit          =[[12th Illinois Infantry]], Company G\n|commands      =\n|battles       =[[American Civil War]]\n*[[Battle of Shiloh]]\n*[[Siege of Corinth]]\n*[[Second Battle of Corinth]]\n*[[Battle of Resaca]]\n*[[Battle of Atlanta]]\n*[[Battle of Jonesborough]]\n*[[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]]\n*[[Battle of Bentonville]]\n|battles_label =\n|awards        =\n|memorials     =\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Sophia Lyter|1865|1900|reason=death}}\n|relations     =\n|laterwork     =Book publisher\n|signature     =\n}}\n'''Alfred Theodore Andreas''' (May 29, 1839 &ndash; February 10, 1900) was an American book publisher and historian.\n\n== Life ==\nHe was born in [[Amity, Orange County, New York|Amity]], [[Orange County, New York|Orange County]], New York, on May 29, 1839.\n\nAfter acquiring an education, he moved to [[Dubuque, Iowa]], where he taught school for some years and conducted business. In 1860, he moved to Illinois.  He enlisted in Company G, [[12th Illinois Infantry]] and served through the American Civil War, rising through the ranks to become a division [[commissary]], serving with Sherman on the [[Sherman's March to the Sea|March to the Sea]] and the Carolina campaigns.<ref name=\"HudsonBergman2009\">{{cite book|author1=David Hudson|author2=Marvin Bergman|author3=Loren Horton|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Iowa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v-cdBfPrxfUC&pg=PA18|date=1 May 2009|publisher=University of Iowa Press|isbn=978-1-58729-724-3|pages=18\u201319|chapter=Alfred Theodore Andreas|others=Mary R. Mcinroy}}</ref> After peace was restored, he moved to [[Davenport, Iowa]], married and for several years was engaged in compiling and publishing county and State atlases, in partnership with [[John Milton Lyter]], who became mayor in 1870. In 1875, he completed and published his greatest work, which was an \"Illustrated Historical Atlas of Iowa.\" It was accurate and became an official authority for real estate dealers, county and State officers. Although many made him substantial profit, others, including his Minnesota and Indiana atlases, were financial failures.<ref name=\"HudsonBergman2009\"/>  Later Andreas moved to Chicago and organized the \u201cWestern Historical Company,\u201d and took up historical writing, publishing a three-volume ''History of Chicago''. He died at [[New Rochelle, New York]], on February 10, 1900.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gue|first=Benjamin F.|title=History of Iowa From the Earliest Times to the Beginning of the Twentieth Century/Volume 4|date=1903|publisher=Century Historical Company|location=New York City|page=7|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/History_of_Iowa_From_the_Earliest_Times_to_the_Beginning_of_the_Twentieth_Century/4/Alfred_T._Andreas}}</ref>\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n*An illustrated historical atlas of Hancock County, Illinois (1874)<ref>[https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto00andr An illustrated historical atlas of Hancock County, Illinois]</ref>\n*An Illustrated Historical Atlas of the State of Minnesota (1874)<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Ristow | first1 = Walter W. | year = 1966 | title = Alfred T. Andreas and His Minnesota Atlas | journal = Minnesota History | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 120\u2013129 | publisher =  Minnesota Historical Society Press | jstor = 20177838 | doi = 10.2307/20177838 | url =  | format = }}</ref>\n*Illustrated Historical Atlas of Iowa (1875)\n*Illustrated historical atlas of the State of Indiana  (1876)<ref>[http://indiamond6.ulib.iupui.edu/cdm/ref/collection/HistAtlas/id/4257 Illustrated historical atlas of the State of Indiana] at Historic Indiana Atlases</ref>\n*History of the State of Nebraska (1882)<ref>[http://www.usgennet.org/usa/ne/topic/resources/andreas/ History of the State of Nebraska]</ref>\n*History of the State of Kansas (1883)<ref>[http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/digital/collections/cul/texts/ldpd_8627113_002/index.html History of the State of Kansas] at [[Columbia University Libraries]]</ref>\n*History of Cook County Illinois (1884)\n*Historical Atlas of Dakota (1884)\n*History of Chicago (3 vols., 1884\u201386)<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historychicagoo00andrgoog History of Chicago (1975 ed.)]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[[:File:Christ Church Red Wing 1874.jpg|Christ Episcopal Church (Red Wing, MN), engraving from the Minnesota Atlas]]\n*{{Find a Grave|30685421|Capt Alfred Theodore Andreas}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andreas, Alfred T.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Warwick, New York]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People of Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Davenport, Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "Bobamnertiopsis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected bibliography:del nonexistent doi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_T._Andreas"}
