ffice)]] [[United Nations Development Programme]] |website=hdr.undp.org |access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref> ([[List of countries by Human Development Index|98th]])\n*0.557 [[List of countries by inequality-adjusted HDI|IHDI]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/table-3-inequality-adjusted-human-development-index-ihdi |title=Inequality-adjusted Human Development Index (IHDI) |publisher=[[Human Development Report|HDRO (Human Development Report Office)]] [[United Nations Development Programme]] |website=hdr.undp.org |access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>}}\n|edbr            = {{increase}} [[Ease of doing business index#Ranking|162nd (below average, 2020)]]<ref name=\" World Bank and International Financial Corporation \">{{cite web |url=http://www.doingbusiness.org/data/exploreeconomies/suriname |title=Ease of Doing Business in Suriname |publisher=Doingbusiness.org |accessdate=2017-01-25 }}</ref>\n|labor           = 165,600 (2007)\n|occupations     = agriculture: 8%; industry: 14%; services: 78% (2004)\n|unemployment    = 9% (2008)\n|industries      = [[bauxite]] and [[gold mining]], [[alumina]] production; [[oil]], [[lumbering]], [[food processing]], [[fishing]]\n|exports         = {{decrease}}$2.149 billion (2014 est.)\n|export-goods    = [[alumina]], [[gold]], [[crude oil]], [[lumber]], [[shrimp]] and [[fish]], [[rice]], [[banana]]s\n|export-partners = {{flag|Switzerland}} 21.8% <br> {{flag|UAE}} 14.5% <br> {{flag|India}} 13.9% <br> {{flag|Belgium}} 9.7% <br> {{flag|United States}} 8.9% <br> {{flag|France}} 8.1% <br> {{flag|Canada}} 6.6% (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2050.html#ns|title=Export Partners of Suriname|publisher=[[CIA World Factbook]]|year=2015|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n|imports         = {{increase}}$1.838 billion (2012 est.)\n|import-goods    = [[capital equipment]], [[petroleum]], [[foodstuff]]s, [[cotton]], [[consumer goods]]\n|import-partners = {{flag|United States}} 26.8% <br> {{flag|Netherlands}} 14.3% <br> {{flag|China}} 12.2% <br> {{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}} 7.4% <br> {{flag|Japan}} 4.8% (2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2061.html#ns|title=Import Partners of Suriname|publisher=[[CIA World Factbook]]|year=2015|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n|FDI             = \n|gross external debt = $504.3 million (2005 est.)\n|debt            = \n|revenue         = $826.6 million (2010 est.)\n|expenses        = $939.7 million (2010 est.)\n|aid             = Netherlands provided $37 million for project and program assistance, European Development Fund $4 million, Belgium $2 million (2003)\n|credit          = [[Standard & Poor's]]:<ref>{{cite web |title= Sovereigns rating list |publisher=Standard & Poor's |url=http://www.standardandpoors.com/ratings/sovereigns/ratings-list/en/eu/?subSectorCode=39 |accessdate=26 May 2011}}</ref><br>BB- (Domestic)<br>B+ (Foreign)<br>BB- (T&C Assessment)<br>Outlook: Positive<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |title=How Fitch, Moody's and S&P rate each country's credit rating |date=15 April 2011 |first1=Simon |last1=Rogers |first2=Ami |last2=Sedghi |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/apr/30/credit-ratings-country-fitch-moodys-standard |accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref><br>[[Moody's]]:<ref name=guardian/><br>B1<br>Outlook: Stable<br>[[Fitch Group|Fitch]]:<ref name=guardian/><br>B<br>Outlook: Positive\n|reserves        = $263.3 million (2006)\n|cianame         = ns\n|spelling        = \n}}\n\nThe '''economy of Suriname''' was largely dependent upon the exports of [[aluminium oxide]] and small amounts of [[aluminium]] produced from [[bauxite]] mined in the country. However after the departure of [[Alcoa]], the economy depended on the exports of [[Petroleum| Crude oil]] and [[gold]]. [[Suriname]] was ranked the 124th safest investment destination in the world in the March 2011 Euromoney Country Risk rankings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Euromoney Country Risk|url=http://www.euromoneycountryrisk.com/|work=Euromoney Country Risk|publisher=Euromoney Institutional Investor PLC|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Bauxite ==\n[[File:En explore explore tree map hs export sur all show 2012.png|thumb|left|Export Trading Treemap of 2012]]\nThe backbone of Suriname's economy is the export of [[aluminium oxide]] (alumina) and small amounts of [[aluminium]] produced from [[bauxite]] mined in the country. In 1999, the [[aluminium]] [[smelter]] at [[Paranam]] was closed<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.alcoa.com/suriname/en/info_page/home.asp | title=Alcoa in Surinam | publisher=Alcoa | accessdate=2013-04-21}}</ref> and mining at [[Onverdacht]] ceased; however, alumina exports accounted for 72% of Suriname's estimated export earnings of [[US dollar|US$]]496.6 million in 2001. Suriname's bauxite deposits have been among the world's richest.\n\nInexpensive power costs are Suriname's big advantage in the energy-intensive alumina and aluminium business. In the 1960s, the Aluminum Company of America ([[Alcoa]]) built the US$150-million Afobaka Dam<ref>{{cite web | url=http://geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-1351582&fid=4449&c=suriname | title=Afobaka Dam: Suriname | publisher=National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency, Bethesda, MD, USA | accessdate=2013-04-21}}</ref> for the production of [[hydroelectric]] energy. This created the [[Brokopondo Reservoir]] a 1,560&nbsp;km\u00b2 lake, one of the largest artificial lakes in the world.\n\n===West Suriname Plan===\n{{Main|West Suriname Plan}}\nIn 1976\u20131977, a 100&nbsp;km long single track [[railway]] was constructed by [[Washington Group International#Morrison Knudsen Co.|Morrison-Knudsen Co.]] in West Suriname from the bauxite containing [[Bakhuis Mountains]] to the town of [[Apoera]] on the [[Courantyne River|Corantijn river]], to transport bauxite by river to processing plants elsewhere. The construction of this railway was financially funded by the Dutch government's independence/severance payments after November 25, 1975. After completion of this railway and associated facilities, for political and economical reasons it was never actually used and was left to be overgrown by the [[jungle]]. Also plans to construct a dam in the [[Kabalebo River]] were developed but never fully executed.\n\nIn 1984, {{Ill|SURALCO|Suralco|nl}}, a subsidiary of [[Alcoa]], formed a [[joint venture]] with the (at that time) [[Royal Dutch Shell]]-owned [[Billiton]] Company, which did not process the bauxite it mined in Suriname. Under this agreement, both companies share risks and profits.\n\nThe major mining sites at [[Moengo]] and [[Lelydorp]] are maturing, and it is now estimated that their reserves will be depleted by 2006. Other proven reserves exist in the east, west, and north of the country sufficient to last until 2045. However, distance and [[topography]] make their immediate development costly. In October 2002, Alcoa and [[BHP Billiton]] signed a letter of intent as the basis for new joint ventures between the two companies, in which Alcoa will take part for 55% in all bauxite mining activities in West Suriname. The government and the companies are looking into cost-effective ways to develop the new mines. The preeminence of bauxite and ALCOA's continued presence in Suriname is a key element in the U.S.-Suriname economic relationship.\n\n== Gold mining ==\nThere is one large scale gold mine operating in Suriname. This is the [[Rosebel Gold Mine]]. Development of a second large scale mine called the Merian Gold Project was approved by the government of Suriname on June 7, 2013. This mining project would be a partnership of [[Newmont Mining Corporation]] and [[Alcoa World Alumina and Chemicals]]. Merian is about {{convert|40|mi|km|order=flip|sigfig=1}} south of the town of [[Moengo, Suriname|Moengo]] on the [[Maroni (river)|Marowijne River]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newmont.com/south-america/merian-gold-project-suriname | title=Merian Gold Project, Suriname | accessdate=2013-05-10 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130319021042/http://newmont.com/south-america/merian-gold-project-suriname | archivedate=2013-03-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/08/suriname-newmont-idUSL1N0EK0J320130608 | title=Suriname lawmakers approve Newmont gold mining deal | work=Reuters | date=June 8, 2013 | accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref> The government estimates there are another 20,000 small scale operators. Only 115 of these were registered by the government in 2009. The government calls these people porknokkers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.caribbeannewsnow.com/topstory-Suriname-government-starts-structuring-gold-mining-industry-4401.html | title=Suriname government starts structuring gold mining industry | publisher=Caribbean News Now | date=January 11, 2011 | accessdate=2013-05-10 | author=Cairo, Ivan}}</ref> Because of unemployment in Suriname, some local people turn to small, illegal gold mining as their source of incomes. Gold mining has caused environmental damages in the country.\n\n=== Commission for the Ordering of the Gold Mining Sector ===\n;Establishment of Ordening Goudsector (OGS)\n\nCommission for the Ordering of the Gold Mining Sector (OGS) was established by the government in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribbeannewsnow.com/topstory-Suriname-government-starts-structuring-gold-mining-industry-4401.html|title=Suriname government starts structuring gold mining industry - Caribbean News Now|website=Caribbeannewsnow.com|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribbeanlifenews.com/stories/2011/1/2011_01_19_wilkinson_suriname.html|title=Suriname moves to end chaos in its gold sector|work=Caribbean Life|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> OGS is leading the reform effort to develop sustainable and environmentally responsible gold mining practices and transform informal small-scale gold mining into a viable sub-sector of the mining and national economy of Suriname.<ref name=\"gov.sr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.sr/media/789355/status_of_the_ordening_goudsector__march_2013_.pdf|title=The Suriname Small Scale Gold Mining Sector|last=|first=|date=|website=Gov.sr|format=PDF|accessdate=8 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023227/http://www.gov.sr/media/789355/status_of_the_ordening_goudsector__march_2013_.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;Ban on mercury use in small-scale mining\n\nSuriname does not produce chemical mercury and only allows mercury imports with a license. Since the 1990s these licenses were not issued anymore. Moreover, all licenses are used for mercury imports for medical use or research. Therefore, trade and import in mercury is illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.sr/media/790227/besluit_negatieve_lijst_2003_en_wijzigingen.pdf|format=PDF|title=Government Act|website=Gov.sr|accessdate=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023234/http://www.gov.sr/media/790227/besluit_negatieve_lijst_2003_en_wijzigingen.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Mercury is used in the small-scale gold mining because smuggling made mercury available. However people who are caught with mercury in their possession will be judged and/or fined.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/11423|title=Starnieuws - US$ 4000 boete voor bezit kwik|website=Starnieuws.com|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nospang.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=30636:aanhouding-braziliaanse-met-60-kilogram-kwik&catid=73:binnenland&Itemid=65|title=NoSpang - Suriname Network Online|website=Nospang.org|accessdate=11 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613115921/http://www.nospang.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=30636:aanhouding-braziliaanse-met-60-kilogram-kwik&catid=73:binnenland&Itemid=65|archive-date=13 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnieuws.com/index.php/welcome/index/nieuwsitem/16013|title=Starnieuws - Nimos zet eerste stap naar uitbanning kwikgebruik|website=Starnieuws.com|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"dwtonline.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwtonline.com/de-ware-tijd/2013/03/16/nimos-neemt-aanloop-uitbanning-kwikgebruik/|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615201027/http://www.dwtonline.com/de-ware-tijd/2013/03/16/nimos-neemt-aanloop-uitbanning-kwikgebruik/|url-status=dead|title=Nimos neemt aanloop uitbanning kwikgebruik - DWTonline.com|accessdate=July 22, 2019|archive-date=June 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Foreign investment\n\nOn April 13, 2013, the government reached an agreement with multinational IAMGOLD to increase investment in Suriname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iamgold.com/English/News/News-Releases/News-Release-Details/2013/IAMGOLD-definitive-agreement-with-Government-of-Suriname-approved-by-National-Assembly/default.aspx|title=IAMGOLD - IAMGOLD definitive agreement with Government of Suriname approved by National Assembly|website=Iamgold.com|accessdate=11 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613083411/http://iamgold.com/English/News/News-Releases/News-Release-Details/2013/IAMGOLD-definitive-agreement-with-Government-of-Suriname-approved-by-National-Assembly/default.aspx|archivedate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1145739/iamgold-definitive-agreement-with-government-of-suriname-approved-by-national-assembly|title=IAMGOLD Corporation - IAMGOLD definitive agreement with Government of Suriname approved by National Assembly|website=Newswire.ca|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n;Kaloti Mint House Suriname\n\nOn March 1, 2013, Kaloti Mint House Suriname laid its funding stone and is expected to start its refinery production by the first quarter of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tradearabia.com/news/IND_232354.html|title=Dubai\u2019s Kaloti to set up gold refinery in Surinam|website=Tradearabia.com|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> Kaloti Mint House will be instrumental in producing \u201cclean gold\u201d in Suriname.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dwtonline.com/de-ware-tijd/2013/03/13/kaloti-mint-house-will-not-cause-pollution/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315140040/http://www.dwtonline.com/de-ware-tijd/2013/03/13/kaloti-mint-house-will-not-cause-pollution/ |archivedate=2013-03-15 }}</ref> Kaloti Mint House have been awarded the ISO 9001:2000 certification for gold and bullion manufacturing and ISO 14001 Environmental Certification. The company is presently applying for ISO 14025 for the Assaying of Gold and Silver. Kaloti will focus on melting and producing gold bars to international standards (999.9 purity) for local and international markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kalotico.com/our_factory.php|title=Precious Metal Services & Solutions in Dubai: Kalotico.com|website=Kalotico.com}}</ref>\n\n;Minamata Treaty\n\nIn October 2013, the UN wants to adopt the Minamata Treaty to ban the user of mercury altogether in Suriname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unep.org/newscentre/default.aspx?DocumentID=2702&ArticleID=9373|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209193047/http://unep.org/newscentre/Default.aspx?DocumentID=2702&ArticleID=9373|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 February 2014|title=Minamata Convention Agreed by Nations|website=Unep.org|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.sr/media/789522/draft_text_minamata_treaty.pdf|format=PDF|title=Draft text for a global legally binding instrument on mercury|website=Gov.sr|accessdate=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924023232/http://www.gov.sr/media/789522/draft_text_minamata_treaty.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;The School of Mining\n\nThe Government initiated a training unit within the Ordening Goudsector called the School of Mining.<ref name=\"gov.sr\"/> This training unit consists of 14 teachers. The teacher's training started February 2013 and is aimed at preparing them for the fieldwork. The duties of the teachers will be to provide hands-on training on the goldfields to small-scale gold miners. The teachers begin with prospecting and showing the small-scale miners more efficient ways to mine in their areas. Along the way they promote mercury free production methods. The Management of Ordening Goudsector hypothesizes that showing small-scale gold miners the benefits of new production methods will be the incentive itself to start the training programs.\n\n<ref name=\"dwtonline.com\"/>\n\n;Entrepreneurial Credit Fund\n\nThe Ministry of Finance initiated a credit fund in March 2013 for small and medium scale entrepreneurs. Small-scale miners can become formally verified entrepreneurs as the piece of land will be viewed as a formal \u201ctitle\u201d by financial institutes. This means the miners will be eligible for credits and thus can acquire credit to upscale their production. A first amount of 35 million SRD (US$10.69 million, as of Monday, Apr 08, 2013, 04:15 PM GMT) is available for credit through the Central Bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbvs.sr/highlights/191-macro-economic-policy-overview|title=Error 404 - Centrale Bank van Suriname|author=Super User|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n;Mining zones\n\nThe Mining Law says that one can only mine with a license from the Government. Ordening Goudsector regulates the concessionaires, how many machine owners there are and what the movements of small-scale miners are.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.sr/sr/kabinet-van-de-president/documenten/ordening-goudsector/wetgeving-en-relevante-docs.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313141209/http://gov.sr/sr/kabinet-van-de-president/documenten/ordening-goudsector/wetgeving-en-relevante-docs.aspx |archivedate=2016-03-13 }}</ref> New mining areas are still being issued. However it is important to note that data show that the interesting area to mine, especially for the small-scale miners who look for alluvial gold, is the [[Greenstone belt]]. The greenstone runs from Guyana, through Suriname, into French Guyana. This greenstone belt, however, only counts for 15% of the Surinamese surface. At the moment almost all areas in this belt are already given out in concessions.\n\n== Foreign aid ==\nAfter the return to a more or less democratically elected government in 1991, Dutch aid resumed. The Dutch relationship continues to be an important factor in the economy, with the Dutch insisting that Suriname undertake economic reforms and produce specific plans acceptable to the Dutch for projects on which aid funds could be spent. In 2000, however, the Dutch revised the structure of their aid package and signaled to the Surinamese authorities their decision to disburse aid by sectoral priorities as opposed to individual projects. Although the present government is not in favor of this approach, it has identified sectors and is now working on sectoral analyses to present to the Dutch.\n\nAfter a short respite in 1991\u20131996, when measures taken in 1993 led to economic stabilization, a relatively stable exchange rate, low [[inflation]], sustainable fiscal policies, and growth, Suriname's economic situation deteriorated from 1996 to the present. This was due in large part to loose fiscal policies of the Wijdenbosch government, which, in the face of lower Dutch development aid, financed its deficit through credit extended by the central bank. As a consequence, the parallel market for foreign exchange soared so that by the end of 1998, the premium of the parallel market rate over the official rate was 85%. Since over 90% of import transactions took place at the parallel rate, inflation took off, with 12-month inflation growing from 0.5% at the end of 1996, to 23% at the end of 1998, and 113% at the end of 1999. The government also instituted a regime of stringent economic controls over prices, the exchange rate, imports, and exports, in an effort to contain the adverse efforts of its economic policies. The cumulative impact of soaring inflation, an unstable exchange rate, and falling real incomes led to a political crisis.\n\nDutch aid stopped to a large extent after [[D\u00e9si Bouterse]] was elected president. Aid from [[China]] has increased.<ref>{{cite news |title=With Aid and Migrants, China Expands Its Presence in a South American Nation |author= [[Simon Romero]]  |date= April 10, 2011 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/11/world/americas/11suriname.html?_r=3&ref=global-home& |accessdate=25 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nSuriname elected a new government in May 2000, but until it was replaced, the [[Wijdenbosch]] government continued its loose fiscal and monetary policies. By the time it left office, the exchange rate in the [[parallel market]] had depreciated further, over 10% of [[GDP]] had been borrowed to finance the fiscal deficit, and there was a significant [[monetary overhang]] in the country. The new government dealt with these problems by devaluing the official exchange rate by 88%, eliminating all other exchange rates except the parallel market rate set by the banks and cambios, raising tariffs on water and electricity, and eliminating the [[subsidy]] on [[gasoline]]. The new administration also rationalized the extensive list of price controls to 12 basic food items. More important, the government ceased all financing from the [[central bank]]. It is attempting to broaden its economic base, establish better contacts with other nations and international financial institutions, and reduce its dependence on Dutch assistance. However, to date the government has yet to implement an investment law or to begin [[privatization]] of any of the 110 parastatal, nor has it given much indication that it has developed a comprehensive plan to develop the economy.\n\n== Oil ==\n[[Oil]] is a promising sector. [[Staatsolie]], the state-owned oil company, produced {{convert|16200|oilbbl|m3}} a day in 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.staatsolie.com/pdf/jaarverslag-staatsolie-final-20052013.pdf | title=Annual Report 2012 | publisher=Staatsolie | accessdate=September 10, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206204612/http://staatsolie.com/pdf/jaarverslag-staatsolie-final-20052013.pdf | archivedate=December 6, 2013 }}</ref> Staatsolie currently refines {{convert|7350|oilbbl|m3}} a day at Tout Lui Faut in\nthe District of Wanica and is building more capacity to go to {{convert|15000|oilbbl|m3}} a day.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.staatsolie.com/pdf/company_profile2012.pdf | title=Company Profile | publisher=Staatsolie | accessdate=September 10, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130203020108/http://www.staatsolie.com/pdf/company_profile2012.pdf | archivedate=February 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Hardwood ==\nSome big companies are getting the [[hardwood]] out of the jungle. However, proposals for exploitation of the country's tropical forests and undeveloped regions of the interior traditionally inhabited by indigenous and [[Maroon (people)|Maroon]] communities have raised the concerns of environmentalists and [[human rights]] activists both in Suriname and abroad. These opposing parties are not yet strong in Suriname.\n\n== Banana ==\nState-owned banana producer [[Surland]] closed its doors on April 5, 2002, after its inability to meet payroll expenses for the second month in a row; it is still unclear if Surland will survive this crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agf.nl/nieuwsbericht_detail.asp?id=26663|title=H\u00e9t branchemedium voor de AGF-sector|website=Agf.nl|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was remodeled as Stichting Behoud Bananen Sector Suriname (SBBS). The rumour was that because of political differences Surland was manipulated in shutting down. The SBBS has made banana profitable for the first time in 20 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parbode.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=544&Itemid=23 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130411144957/http://parbode.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=544&Itemid=23 |archivedate=2013-04-11 }}</ref>\n\n== Other exports ==\nA member of [[CARICOM]], Suriname also exports in small numbers [[rice]], [[shrimp]], [[timber]], [[banana]]s, [[fruit]]s, and [[vegetable]]s.\n\n== Currency ==\nMoreover, in January 2002, the government renegotiated [[civil servant]] wages (a significant part of the work force and a significant portion of government expenditure), agreeing to raises as high as 100%. Pending implementation of these wage increases and concerned that the government may be unable to meet these increased expenses, the local currency weakened from Sf 2200 in January 2002 to nearly Sf 2500 in April 2002. On March 26, 2003, the [[Central Bank of Suriname]] (CBvS) adjusted the [[exchange rate]] of the U.S. dollar. This action resulted in further devaluation of the [[Surinamese guilder]]. The official exchange rate of the US$ was SF 2,650 for selling and SF 2,600 for purchasing. With the official exchange rate, the CBvS came closer to the exchange rate on the parallel market which sold the U.S. dollar for SF 3,250.\n\nFrom 2011: [[Surinamese dollar]] (SRD) = 100 cent; USD 1.00 is ca. SRD 3.20 (May 2011)\n\nFrom 2004 to 2011: [[Surinamese dollar]] (SRD) = 100 cent; USD 1.00 is ca. SRD 2.74 (July 2007)\n\nBefore 2004: [[Surinamese gulden]] (SRG) = 100 cent, SRD 1 = SRG 1000; coins had extremely low official value and a much higher collector's value; their official value has now been multiplied by 1000: the value in SRD cent is equal to the former value in SRG cent. The same applies for \"currency notes\" (SRG 1 and 2.50).\n\nSurinamese guilders per US dollar - 2,346.75 (2002), 2,178.5 (2001), 1,322.47 (2000), 859.44 (1999), 401 (1998) <br>\nNote: during 1998, the exchange rate splintered into four distinct rates; in January 1999 the government floated the guilder, but subsequently fixed it when the black-market rate plunged; the government then allowed trading within a band of SRG 500 around the official rate\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe following table shows the main economic indicators in 1990\u20132017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2018/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=46&pr.y=8&sy=1990&ey=2017&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=366&s=NGDP_RPCH%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC%2CPCPIPCH%2CGGXWDG_NGDP&grp=0&a=|accessdate=2018-09-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Year\n!1990\n!1995\n!2000\n!2005\n!2006\n!2007\n!2008\n!2009\n!2010\n!2011\n!2012\n!2013\n!2014\n!2015\n!2016\n!2017\n|-\n|GDP in $<br /><small>(PPP)</small>\n|2.71 Bln.\n|2.78 Bln.\n|3.63 Bln.\n|5.31 Bln.\n|5.79 Bln.\n|6.24 Bln.\n|6.63 Bln.\n|6.88 Bln.\n|7.33 Bln.\n|7.91 Bln.\n|8.28 Bln.\n|8.66 Bln.\n|8.84 Bln.\n|8.70 Bln.\n|8.36 Bln.\n|8.51 Bln.\n|-\n|GDP per capita in $<br /><small>(PPP)</small>\n|6,644\n|6,348\n|7,783\n|10,647\n|11,476\n|12,243\n|12,823\n|13,130\n|13,792\n|14,658\n|15,282\n|15,734\n|15,812\n|15,334\n|14,539\n|14,606\n|-\n|GDP growth<br /><small>(real)</small>\n|\u22121.5 %\n|11.3 %\n|\u22120.1 %\n|4.9 %\n|5.8 %\n|5.1 %\n|4.1 %\n|3.0 %\n|5.2 %\n|5.8 %\n|2.7 %\n|2.9 %\n|0.3 %\n|\u22122.6 %\n|\u22125.1 %\n|0.0 %\n|-\n|Inflation<br /><small>(in Percent)</small>\n|21.8 %\n|24.2 %\n|29.6 %\n|14.0 %\n|11.3 %\n|6.4 %\n|14.7 %\n|\u22120.3 %\n|6.9 %\n|17.7 %\n|5.0 %\n|1.9 %\n|3.4 %\n|6.9 %\n|55.5 %\n|22.0 %\n|-\n|Debt/GDP<br /><small>(in Percent)</small>\n|78 %\n|17 %\n|38 %\n|29 %\n|24 %\n|17 %\n|16 %\n|16 %\n|18 %\n|20 %\n|21 %\n|30 %\n|26 %\n|43 %\n|76 %\n|72 %\n|}\n\n*Industrial production growth rate: 6.5% (1994 est.)\n*Electricity \u2013 production: 1.58 billion [[kWh]] (2008)\n*Electricity \u2013 production by source:\n*Electricity \u2013 consumption: 1.44 billion kWh (2008)\n**exports: 0 kWh (1998)\n**imports: 0 kWh (1998)\n*Agriculture - products: paddy [[rice]], [[banana]]s, palm kernels, [[coconut]]s, [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]]s, [[peanut]]s; [[beef]], [[chicken]]s; forest products; [[shrimp]]\n*There are no Patent Laws in Suriname.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billanderson.com.au/Gazetteer-Patents.htm|title=Gazetteer - Patents|website=Billanderson.com.au|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[Surinamese dollar]]\n* [[Economy of South America]]\n* [[Central Bank of Suriname]]\n* [[Central banks and currencies of the Caribbean]]\n* [[Dutch Caribbean Securities Exchange]]\n* [[List of countries by credit rating]]\n* [[List of countries by public debt]]\n{{Col-2}}\n* [[List of Latin American and Caribbean countries by GDP growth]]\n* [[List of Latin American and Caribbean countries by GDP (nominal)]]\n* [[List of Latin American and Caribbean countries by GDP (PPP)]]\n* [[List of countries by tax revenue as percentage of GDP]]\n* [[List of countries by future gross government debt]]\n* [[List of countries by leading trade partners]]\n{{Col-end}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/11/world/americas/11suriname.html?_r=2&ref=global-home& With Aid and Migrants, China Expands Its Presence in a South American Nation] in ''The New York Times'' by [[Simon Romero]] published April 10, 2011\n*[http://amazonteam.org/maps/suriname-gold Amazon Gold Rush: Gold Mining in Suriname web map], published October 12, 2015\n\n{{Suriname topics}}\n{{Caricom}}\n{{SACN}}\n{{Americas topic|Economy of}}\n{{World Trade Organization}}\n\n[[Category:World Trade Organization member economies|Suriname]]\n[[